# WordPress Plugin Standards

## Architecture

- Keep plugin modules small and focused.
- Prefer composition over large procedural files.
- Add new hooks/filters for extensibility instead of hard-coded behavior.
- Keep public hook names stable; avoid silent renames.
- Place plugin runtime code only under `mksddn-reddy-auth/trunk`.
- Keep agent docs and config in repository root (`AGENTS.md`, `.cursor/*`, `docs/ai/*`).

## Naming

- Use clear and consistent prefixes for global functions, option keys, and constants.
- Use class names that describe domain intent.
- Keep file names aligned with class/function responsibility.

## WordPress APIs

- Use WordPress APIs for options, metadata, users, HTTP, and cron instead of custom wrappers unless justified.
- Use Settings API for admin settings pages.
- Register assets via `wp_enqueue_script` and `wp_enqueue_style` in proper hooks.
- For lifecycle logic, use `register_activation_hook` and `register_deactivation_hook`.

## Internationalization

- Wrap all user-facing strings in i18n functions.
- Keep one consistent text domain.
- Use escaped translation helpers when rendering into HTML attributes or plain HTML.

## Backward Compatibility

- Do not break existing option names, hook contracts, or persisted data shape without explicit migration.
- If migration is required, implement explicit version checks and migration steps.
